essaggio evocativo dell\u2019arte ai tempi del Coronavirus |url=https://www.ilvaloreitaliano.it/il-messaggio-evocativo-dellarte-ai-tempi-del-coronavirus/ |website=Valore Italiano}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Uncategorized|date=April 2020}}\n", "name_user": "Lopifalko", "label": "safe", "comment": "MOS:COMMONWORDS", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Giovanni_Guida"}
{"title_page": "Beinn Challuim", "text_new": "{{Short description|Scottish mountain in the Loch Lomond and the Trossachs National Park}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Beinn Challuim\n| photo = Beinn Challuim 2.jpg\n| photo_caption = Beinn Challuim seen from the high ground around Crianlarich, 12&nbsp;km to the south.\n| elevation_m = 1025\n| elevation_ref = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/munros/ben-challum |title= walkhighlands Ben Challum |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |publisher=walkhighlands.co.uk |accessdate=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n| prominence_m = 450\n| prominence_ref = \n| listing = [[Munro]], [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]]\n| translation = Malcolm\u2019s Peak\n| language = [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]]\n| pronunciation = {{IPA-gd|pe\u0272 \u02c8xal\u032a\u02e0\u0259m|lang}}\n| location = [[Stirling (council area)|Stirling]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Grampian Mountains (Scotland)|Grampians]]\n| grid_ref_UK = NN386322\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 50, [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' 378\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n| map  = Scotland\n}}\n\n{{GB summits start}}\n{{GB summits entry\n|Name=South Top\n|Gridref=NN386315\n|Height=998&nbsp;m (3274&nbsp;ft)\n|Status=Munro Top}}\n{{end}}\n\n[[File:Beinn Challuim from the west 2.jpg|thumb|right|300px|This view from the west shows both the main summit (left) and the South Top (right) of Beinn Challuim.]]\n'''Beinn Challuim''' ({{lang-en|'''Ben Challum'''}}) is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] mountain in the very northern part of the [[Loch Lomond and the Trossachs National Park]] six kilometres east northeast of the village of [[Tyndrum]] in the [[Stirling Council]] area. The mountain stands in the Forest of Mamlorn, an ancient [[deer forest]] in Breadalbane.\n\n== Overview ==\nWith a  height of 1025 metres (3363&nbsp;feet) and a [[Topographic prominence|prominence]] of 450 metres (1480&nbsp;feet) Ben Challuim qualifies as a [[Munro]] and a [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]]. It stands at the head of [[Glen Lochay]] and is a prominent peak when seen from the head of that glen, its western slopes dominate the north eastern side of Strath Fillan. When seen from the south the summit of the mountain cannot be seen, being hidden behind the south top. The mountain name was originally written as Beinn Challuim before Ben Challum became the norm. However in recent years the [[Ordnance Survey]] have reverted to using the original name on their maps.\n\nThe name translates as \u201cMalcolm\u2019s mountain\u201d but it is believed that the older spelling could possibly refer to Saint [[Columba]] who is known in [[Scottish Gaelic]] as \"Calum Cille\". With St. [[Fillan]]'s priory lying on the south west foothills of the mountain (St Fillan brought Christianity from the monastery of St Columba on Iona into Breadalbane),<ref name=\"test2\">[http://www.wild-cat.demon.co.uk/history.htm A Short History of Breadalbane.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704050513/http://www.wild-cat.demon.co.uk/history.htm |date=July 4, 2007 }} \"St Fillan brought Christianity from the monastery of St Columba on Iona into Breadalbane\" .</ref> the Columba connection is feasible. Some guide books give the translation as \u201cCalum\u2019s Peak\".<ref name=\"test3\">\"The Magic of the Munros\" Page 35 (Gives rest of details on name origins and translation).</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nBeinn Challuim is often regarded as a smooth grassy hill mainly because these are the characteristics of the southern and western slopes which are seen by many people from the [[A82 road]] around Strath Fillan. However from the north it shows a more exciting form with a steep and rocky face overlooking the head of Glen Lochay. Beinn Challuim is made up of three ridges, the broad grassy south west ridge descends to Strath Fillan and is used in ascents from there. The north west ridge is steep and rocky and descends to the [[Mountain pass|Bealach]] Ghlas-Leathaid (575 metres) and then connects to the [[List of Corbetts|Corbett]] of Cam Chreag. Another ridge goes easterly, descending into Glen Lochay.\n\nThe mountain has a subsidiary summit which is listed in the Munro Tables as a \u201cTop\u201d, The '''South Top''' reaches a height of 998 metres and lies 600 metres south of the highest point.<ref name=\"test4\">[http://www.hills-database.co.uk/downloads.html Database of British and Irish Hills.]</ref> The two summits are connected by a ridge and this area can be confusing in poor visibility with the logical temptation to go north to the main summit possibly resulting in encountering steep crags. The proper route from the south top is to go initially west for a short distance across a hollow and onto the ridge which leads north to the main summit.<ref name=\"test5\">[http://www.incallander.co.uk/walks/benchallum.htm www.incallander.co.uk.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926223539/http://www.incallander.co.uk/walks/benchallum.htm |date=September 26, 2007 }} Gives details of dangers of summit ridge.</ref> The summit ridge has two [[Cirque|corries]] on either side, to the west is the Coire nan Each (Corrie of the Horse) and to the east is Coire Challuim (Malcolm's Corrie). Drainage from the mountain reaches both coasts of Scotland at the [[Firth of Tay]] on the east coast and the [[Firth of Clyde]] on the west coast.\n\n== Ascents and summit ==\nThe most popular route of ascent starts at Kirkton Farm in Strath Fillan (grid reference {{gbm4ibx|NN358280}}), this gives the opportunity to visit the ruins of St. Fillans Priory at the beginning or end of the walk. The route continues north east up grassy slopes to reach the summit ridge.<ref name=\"test6\">\"The Munros\" Page 37 (Gives details of ascent from Strath Fillan).</ref> A more interesting ascent starts at the road end in Glen Lochay, this gives the chance to view the more noteworthy northern side of the mountain but involves a nine kilometre walk up the glen to the foot of the eastern ridge.<ref name=\"test7\">\"The High Mountains of Britain and Ireland\" Pages 65 (Details ascent from head of Glen Lochay).</ref> [[Hamish Brown]] recommends a northern approach starting at Auch (grid reference {{gbm4ibx|NN324355}}) \u201cif you want to be different\u201d but this requires good navigation and some mild scrambling up the north west ridge.<ref name=\"test8\">\"Hamish's Mountain Walk\" Page 73 (Suggests ascent from Auch).</ref>\n\nThe actual summit of the mountain is named as Stob Glas (greenish-grey peak) on maps and has a large [[cairn]] which overlooks the sheer northern face. The view from the top gives fine views of the many peaks around the Tyndrum and [[Crianlarich]] area.\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category|Beinn Challuim}}\n*''The Munros'', Scottish Mountaineering Trust, 1986, Donald Bennett (Editor) {{ISBN|0-907521-13-4}}\n*''The High Mountains of Britain and Ireland'', Diadem, 1993, [[Irvine Butterfield]], {{ISBN|0-906371-30-9}}\n*''The Munros, Scotland's Highest Mountains'', [[Cameron McNeish]], {{ISBN|1-84204-082-0}}\n*''The Magic Of The Munros'', Irvine Butterfield, {{ISBN|0-7153-2168-4}}\n*''Hamish\u2019s Mountain Walk'', Baton Wicks, 1996, Hamish Brown, {{ISBN|1-898573-08-5}}\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Scottish Munros section 2}}\n\n{{coord|56.454|N|4.6198|W|scale:5000_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Munros]]\n[[Category:Marilyns of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of the Southern Highlands]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Stirling (council area)]]\n[[Category:One-thousanders of the British Isles]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Scottish mountain in the Loch Lomond and the Trossachs National Park}}\n{{Infobox mountain\n| name = Beinn Challuim\n| photo = Beinn Challuim 2.jpg\n| photo_caption = Beinn Challuim seen from the high ground around Crianlarich, 12&nbsp;km to the south.\n| elevation_m = 1025\n| elevation_ref = <ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.walkhighlands.co.uk/munros/ben-challum |title= walkhighlands Ben Challum |author=<!--Staff writer(s); no by-line.--> |year=2013 |publisher=walkhighlands.co.uk |accessdate=26 October 2013}}</ref>\n| prominence_m = 450\n| prominence_ref = \n| listing = [[Munro]], [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]]\n| translation = Malcolm\u2019s Peak\n| language = [[Scottish Gaelic language|Gaelic]]\n| pronunciation = {{IPA-gd|pe\u0272 \u02c8xal\u032a\u02e0\u0259m|lang}}\n| location = [[Stirling (council area)|Stirling]], [[Scotland]]\n| range = [[Grampian Mountains (Scotland)|Grampians]]\n| grid_ref_UK = NN386322\n| topo = [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Landranger'' 50, [[Ordnance Survey|OS]] ''Explorer'' 378\n| first_ascent = \n| easiest_route = \n| map  = Scotland\n}}\n\n{{GB summits start}}\n{{GB summits entry\n|Name=South Top\n|Gridref=NN386315\n|Height=998&nbsp;m (3274&nbsp;ft)\n|Status=Munro Top}}\n{{end}}\n\n[[File:Beinn Challuim from the west 2.jpg|thumb|right|300px|This view from the west shows both the main summit (left) and the South Top (right) of Beinn Challuim.]]\n'''Beinn Challuim''' ({{lang-en|'''Ben Challum'''}}) is a [[Scotland|Scottish]] mountain in the very northern part of the [[Loch Lomond and the Trossachs National Park]] six kilometres east northeast of the village of [[Tyndrum]] in the [[Stirling Council]] area. The mountain stands in the Forest of Mamlorn, an ancient [[deer forest]] in Breadalbane.\n\n== Overview ==\nWith a  height of 1025 metres (3363&nbsp;feet) and a [[Topographic prominence|prominence]] of 450 metres (1480&nbsp;feet) Ben Challuim qualifies as a [[Munro]] and a [[Marilyn (hill)|Marilyn]]. It stands at the head of [[Glen Lochay]] and is a prominent peak when seen from the head of that glen, its western slopes dominate the north eastern side of Strath Fillan. When seen from the south the summit of the mountain cannot be seen, being hidden behind the south top. The mountain name was originally written as Beinn Challuim before Ben Challum became the norm. However in recent years the [[Ordnance Survey]] have reverted to using the original name on their maps.\n\nThe name translates as \u201cMalcolm\u2019s mountain\u201d but it is believed that the older spelling could possibly refer to Saint [[Columba]] who is known in [[Scottish Gaelic]] as \"Calum Cille\". With St. [[Fillan]]'s priory lying on the south west foothills of the mountain (St Fillan brought Christianity from the monastery of St Columba on Iona into Breadalbane),<ref name=\"test2\">[http://www.wild-cat.demon.co.uk/history.htm A Short History of Breadalbane.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070704050513/http://www.wild-cat.demon.co.uk/history.htm |date=July 4, 2007 }} \"St Fillan brought Christianity from the monastery of St Columba on Iona into Breadalbane\" .</ref> the Columba connection is feasible. Some guide books give the translation as \u201cCalum\u2019s Peak\".<ref name=\"test3\">\"The Magic of the Munros\" Page 35 (Gives rest of details on name origins and translation).</ref>\n\n== Geography ==\nBeinn Challuim is often regarded as a smooth grassy hill mainly because these are the characteristics of the southern and western slopes which are seen by many people from the [[A82 road]] around Strath Fillan. However from the north it shows a more exciting form with a steep and rocky face overlooking the head of Glen Lochay. Beinn Challuim is made up of three ridges, the broad grassy south west ridge descends to Strath Fillan and is used in ascents from there. The north west ridge is steep and rocky and descends to the [[Mountain pass|Bealach]] Ghlas-Leathaid (575 metres) and then connects to the [[List of Corbetts|Corbett]] of Cam Chreag. Another ridge goes easterly, descending into Glen Lochay.\n\n{{Short description|Reaches a height of 998 metres and lies 600 metres south of the highest point}}\nThe mountain has a subsidiary summit which is listed in the Munro Tables as a \u201cTop\u201d, The '''South Top''' reaches a height of 998 metres and lies 600 metres south of the highest point.<ref name=\"test4\">[http://www.hills-database.co.uk/downloads.html Database of British and Irish Hills.]</ref> The two summits are connected by a ridge and this area can be confusing in poor visibility with the logical temptation to go north to the main summit possibly resulting in encountering steep crags. The proper route from the south top is to go initially west for a short distance across a hollow and onto the ridge which leads north to the main summit.<ref name=\"test5\">[http://www.incallander.co.uk/walks/benchallum.htm www.incallander.co.uk.] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070926223539/http://www.incallander.co.uk/walks/benchallum.htm |date=September 26, 2007 }} Gives details of dangers of summit ridge.</ref> The summit ridge has two [[Cirque|corries]] on either side, to the west is the Coire nan Each (Corrie of the Horse) and to the east is Coire Challuim (Malcolm's Corrie). Drainage from the mountain reaches both coasts of Scotland at the [[Firth of Tay]] on the east coast and the [[Firth of Clyde]] on the west coast.\n\n== Ascents and summit ==\nThe most popular route of ascent starts at Kirkton Farm in Strath Fillan (grid reference {{gbm4ibx|NN358280}}), this gives the opportunity to visit the ruins of St. Fillans Priory at the beginning or end of the walk. The route continues north east up grassy slopes to reach the summit ridge.<ref name=\"test6\">\"The Munros\" Page 37 (Gives details of ascent from Strath Fillan).</ref> A more interesting ascent starts at the road end in Glen Lochay, this gives the chance to view the more noteworthy northern side of the mountain but involves a nine kilometre walk up the glen to the foot of the eastern ridge.<ref name=\"test7\">\"The High Mountains of Britain and Ireland\" Pages 65 (Details ascent from head of Glen Lochay).</ref> [[Hamish Brown]] recommends a northern approach starting at Auch (grid reference {{gbm4ibx|NN324355}}) \u201cif you want to be different\u201d but this requires good navigation and some mild scrambling up the north west ridge.<ref name=\"test8\">\"Hamish's Mountain Walk\" Page 73 (Suggests ascent from Auch).</ref>\n\nThe actual summit of the mountain is named as Stob Glas (greenish-grey peak) on maps and has a large [[cairn]] which overlooks the sheer northern face. The view from the top gives fine views of the many peaks around the Tyndrum and [[Crianlarich]] area.\n\n== References ==\n{{commons category|Beinn Challuim}}\n*''The Munros'', Scottish Mountaineering Trust, 1986, Donald Bennett (Editor) {{ISBN|0-907521-13-4}}\n*''The High Mountains of Britain and Ireland'', Diadem, 1993, [[Irvine Butterfield]], {{ISBN|0-906371-30-9}}\n*''The Munros, Scotland's Highest Mountains'', [[Cameron McNeish]], {{ISBN|1-84204-082-0}}\n*''The Magic Of The Munros'', Irvine Butterfield, {{ISBN|0-7153-2168-4}}\n*''Hamish\u2019s Mountain Walk'', Baton Wicks, 1996, Hamish Brown, {{ISBN|1-898573-08-5}}\n'''Footnotes'''\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Scottish Munros section 2}}\n\n{{coord|56.454|N|4.6198|W|scale:5000_region:GB|display=title}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Munros]]\n[[Category:Marilyns of Scotland]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of the Southern Highlands]]\n[[Category:Mountains and hills of Stirling (council area)]]\n[[Category:One-thousanders of the British Isles]]\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eGeography:partial rv self", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Beinn_Challuim"}
{"title_page": "Qishlah", "text_new": "{{short description|Palace in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|date=May 2015}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n\n[[Image:Qishlah Palace.jpg|thumb|'''Qishlah''' palace in [[Ha'il]]]]\n'''Qishlah''' or '''Al-Qishlah''' (Arabic:\u0642\u0635\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0634\u0644\u0629) is a Palace in the center of [[Ha'il]] city, [[Saudi Arabia]]. Built in the 1940s during the principality of prince Abdul-Aziz bin Musa'ad Al Saud of Ha'il province. It is a two-floor mud palace, 142.8x141.2 meters, its walls are 8.5m high, and it has eight watch-towers along with the walls with two main gates, east and west.\n\n'''Qishlah''' comes from the [[Turkish language|Turkish]] word for [[fort]] or [[barracks]] (K\u0131\u015fla). The purpose of building it was to make it the central location for the army troops arriving there. Then it was a prison until the end of the principality of bin Musa'ad, when it was re-purposed as a historical building by the government.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|27.51906|N|41.69442|E|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n\n{{Castles in Saudi Arabia}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1943]]\n[[Category:Palaces in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Forts in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Castles in Saudi Arabia]]\n\n\n{{Palace-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Palace in Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Short description|Palace in Ha'il, Saudi Arabia]]\n'''Qishlah''' or '''Al-Qishlah''' (Arabic:\u0642\u0635\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0634\u0644\u0629) is a palace in the center of Ha'il city, Saudi Arabia}}\n{{Multiple issues|\n{{notability|date=May 2015}}\n{{Unreferenced|date=May 2015}}\n}}\n\n[[Image:Qishlah Palace.jpg|thumb|'''Qishlah''' palace in [[Ha'il]]]]\n'''Qishlah''' or '''Al-Qishlah''' (Arabic:\u0642\u0635\u0631 \u0627\u0644\u0642\u0634\u0644\u0629) is a Palace in the center of [[Ha'il]] city, [[Saudi Arabia]]. Built in the 1940s during the principality of prince Abdul-Aziz bin Musa'ad Al Saud of Ha'il province. It is a two-floor mud palace, 142.8x141.2 meters, its walls are 8.5m high, and it has eight watch-towers along with the walls with two main gates, east and west.\n\n'''Qishlah''' comes from the [[Turkish language|Turkish]] word for [[fort]] or [[barracks]] (K\u0131\u015fla). The purpose of building it was to make it the central location for the army troops arriving there. Then it was a prison until the end of the principality of bin Musa'ad, when it was re-purposed as a historical building by the government.\n\n==Notes==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{coord|27.51906|N|41.69442|E|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n{{Portal|Saudi Arabia}}\n\n{{Castles in Saudi Arabia}}\n\n[[Category:Houses completed in 1943]]\n[[Category:Palaces in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Forts in Saudi Arabia]]\n[[Category:Castles in Saudi Arabia]]\n\n\n{{Palace-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Rich Farmbrough", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:partial rv self", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Qishlah"}
{"title_page": "Indian Institute of Management Tiruchirappalli", "text_new": "{{Use Indian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name           = Indian Institute of Management Tiruchirappalli\n| native_name = \n|image_size      =\n| motto          =\n| motto_lang     =\n| mottoeng       = Knowledge is Endless\n| established    = {{start date |2011}}\n| type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]] [[business school]]\n|chairman        = Jalaj Dani<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pathak|first1=Vikas|title=Four IIMs to get new chairmen|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/four-iims-to-get-new-chairmen/article19695142.ece|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=16 September 2017|language=en-IN}}</ref>\n| director       =  Bhimaraya Metri<ref>{{Cite web\n |url= http://www.iimtrichy.ac.in/director-message\n |title=Profile}}</ref>\n| city           = [[Tiruchirappalli]]\n| state          = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| country        = [[India]]\n|coor = {{coord|10|39|49|N|78|44|41|E|region:IN_type:edu}}\n| campus         = [[Suburban area|Suburban]]\n|website         = {{URL|www.iimtrichy.ac.in}}\n|image_name      = IIM_Trichy_Logo.png\n}}\n\nThe '''Indian Institute of Management Tiruchirappalli''' (also known as '''IIM T''' or '''IIM Trichy''') is a public graduate [[business school]] located on [[Tiruchirappalli]]-[[Pudukkottai]]  [[National Highway 336 (India)|National Highway 336]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. Founded in 2011, it is one of the seven [[Indian Institutes of Management]] the Indian government had set up during the [[Eleventh Five-Year Plan (India)|Eleventh Five-Year Plan]]<ref>{{Cite news\n |url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-03-29/india/27744779_1_iits-in-andhra-pradesh-iims-central-universities\n |title=Proposed IIMs | work=The Times Of India | date=29 March 2008}}</ref> and was mentored by [[IIM Bangalore]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mbauniverse.com/article/id/4101/IIM-Trichy |title=Foundation laid |access-date=6 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907035159/http://www.mbauniverse.com/article/id/4101/IIM-Trichy |archive-date=7 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was the 11th IIM to be set up in India. Classes for the first batch began on 15 June 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article2108504.ece |title=The Hindu : NATIONAL / TAMIL NADU : IIM-Tiruchi off to a bright start |work=thehindu.com |accessdate=9 October 2011 |location=Chennai, India |date=16 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nThe institute temporarily operated at [[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]] campus and the permanent campus was inaugurated on 3 April 2017 by [[Prakash Javadekar]].<ref name=\"Narasimhan\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/management/iim-trichy-to-become-global-institute-in-10-years-management-116100900130_1.html|title=IIM-Trichy to become global institute in 10 years: Management|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|date=2016-10-09|newspaper=Business Standard India|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/report-prakash-javadekar-to-inaugurate-new-campus-building-for-iim-tiruchirapalli-2379442|title=Prakash Javadekar to inaugurate new campus building for IIM Tiruchirapalli {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=2017-04-03|work=dna|access-date=2017-04-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIndian Institute of Management Tiruchirappalli's permanent campus is located on a {{convert|172.27|acre}} land.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/on-campus/iim-trichy-starts-work-on-new-172-acre-campus/article6152112.ece |title=IIM Trichy starts work on new 172 acre campus |location=[[Trichy]] |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=26 June 2014}}</ref> In its full shape, the {{INRConvert|584|c}} permanent campus will consist of student hostels, faculty residences, a library, recreational facilities and a Management Development Centre.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/education/news/IIM-Trichy-to-move-into-its-own-campus-in-2015/articleshow/24725883.cms |title=IIM-Trichy to move into its own campus in 2015 |location=[[Trichy]]|work=[[The Times of India]] |date=26 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Narasimhan\"/>\n\nThe Indian Institute of Management Trichy has set up a satellite campus at Chennai. It offers a two-year postgraduate programme for working professionals from this campus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-07/news/32576765_1_iim-trichy-iim-kozhikode-pgpbm |title=Chennai Campus |location=[[Trichy]]|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=7 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Academic programs==\nIIM Trichy offers a two-year full-time residential Post Graduate Programme in Management (PGP), a two-year Post Graduate Programme in Business Management (PGPBM) for working executives at Chennai campus,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.iimtrichy.ac.in/home/academics/programs/ |title=Programme Offered |access-date=1 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110620081836/http://www.iimtrichy.ac.in/home/academics/programs/ |archive-date=20 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and a Fellow Programme in Management (FPM) for doctoral candidates.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n|type=Institute\n|NIRF_B_2018= 15\n}}\nIIM Tiruchirappalli was ranked 15 in [[National Institutional Ranking Framework]] (NIRF) management school ranking of 2018.<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_B_2018/>\n\n== Events ==\nIIMT hosts several yearly events. Dhruva is a cultural and management [[Cultural Festival (India)|fest]] held in the second half of the month of October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dhruva.iimtrichy.ac.in/index.php|title=Dhruva 16|website=dhruva.iimtrichy.ac.in|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/iim-trichy-celebrates-its-management-and-cultural-fest-dhruva/article9261648.ece|title=IIM Trichy celebrates its management and cultural fest, Dhruva|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2016-10-24|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/dhruva16-a-business-and-cultural-extravaganza/article9132375.ece|title=Dhruva\u201916: A business and cultural extravaganza|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2016-09-21|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> E-Summit is an entrepreneurial summit held in the month of November.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://esummit.iimtrichy.ac.in/|title=E-Summit|website=esummit.iimtrichy.ac.in|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/iim-trichy-conducts-inaugural-edition-of-esummit-2016/article9344999.ece|title=IIM Trichy conducts inaugural edition of E-Summit 2016|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2016-11-14|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> HR Conclave is an industry-academia interaction event focused on [[Human Resources]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrconclave.iimtrichy.ac.in/|title=IIMT -  HR Conclave 2016|last=Trichy|first=IIM|website=hrconclave.iimtrichy.ac.in|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/hr-conclave/article9301971.ece|title=HR conclave|date=2016-11-04|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/iim-trichys-hr-conclave-2015-on-oct-17/article7766335.ece|title=IIM Trichy\u2019s HR Conclave 2015 on Oct 17|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2015-10-15|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/iim-trichy-conducts-its-fourth-hr-conclave/article9312116.ece|title=The role of data analytics in human resource management|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2016-11-06|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> Other events include Sanskriti - an annual war of sections,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideiim.com/Sanskriti-4-0-at-iim-trichy-battle-of-the-sections/|title=Sanskriti 4.0 at IIM Trichy \u2013 Battle of The Sections {{!}} InsideIIM.com|website=insideiim.com|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> Sangram - an inter-IIM sports meet,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportskeeda.com/general-sports/iim-kozhikode-stage-sangram-2015-second-week-november|title=IIM Kozhikode to stage Sangram 2015 in the second week of November|date=2015-11-12|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportskeeda.com/general-sports/inter-iim-sports-meet-sangram-concludes-iim-bangalore-take-victory|title=IIM-Bangalore take top prize at Sangram, the Inter-IIM sports meet|date=2015-11-19|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> and Kurukshetra - an inter-section sports tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://students.iimtrichy.ac.in/|title=IIMT Student Portal|website=students.iimtrichy.ac.in|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref>\n\n== Admission Process ==\nThe admission for the  two-year full-time residential Post Graduate Programme in Management (PGP) is through the Common Admission Test (CAT) scores followed by the Common Admission Process (CAP), where the 10 new and baby IIMs take part. The CAP consists of a written-ability test (WAT) followed by an interview. Based on the past academic performances, work experience, CAT scores and CAP scores, students are offered admission into this program. The total intake for the following batch 2020-22 will be 230 students approximately.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://iimtrichy.ac.in/ Official website]\n\n{{Indian Institutes of Management}}\n{{Tiruchirappalli}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Institute Of Management Tiruchirappalli}}\n[[Category:Indian Institutes of Management|TRICHY]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Tiruchirappalli|IIM]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use Indian English|date=November 2016}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name           = Indian Institute of Management Tiruchirappalli\n| native_name = \n|image_size      =\n| motto          =\n| motto_lang     =\n| mottoeng       = Knowledge is Endless\n| established    = {{start date |2011}}\n| type           = [[Public school (government funded)|Public]] [[business school]]\n|chairman        = Jalaj Dani<ref>{{cite news|last1=Pathak|first1=Vikas|title=Four IIMs to get new chairmen|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/four-iims-to-get-new-chairmen/article19695142.ece|accessdate=11 October 2017|work=[[The Hindu]]|date=16 September 2017|language=en-IN}}</ref>\n| director       =  Bhimaraya Metri<ref>{{Cite web\n |url= http://www.iimtrichy.ac.in/director-message\n |title=Profile}}</ref>\n| city           = [[Tiruchirappalli]]\n| state          = [[Tamil Nadu]]\n| country        = [[India]]\n|coor = {{coord|10|39|49|N|78|44|41|E|region:IN_type:edu}}\n| campus         = [[Suburban area|Suburban]]\n|website         = {{URL|www.iimtrichy.ac.in}}\n|image_name      = IIM_Trichy_Logo.png\n}}\n\nThe '''Indian Institute of Management Tiruchirappalli''' (also known as '''IIM T''' or '''IIM Trichy''') is a public graduate [[business school]] located on [[Tiruchirappalli]]-[[Pudukkottai]]  [[National Highway 336 (India)|National Highway 336]], [[Tamil Nadu]], [[India]]. Founded in 2011, it is one of the seven [[Indian Institutes of Management]] the Indian government had set up during the [[Eleventh Five-Year Plan (India)|Eleventh Five-Year Plan]]<ref>{{Cite news\n |url= http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2008-03-29/india/27744779_1_iits-in-andhra-pradesh-iims-central-universities\n |title=Proposed IIMs | work=The Times Of India | date=29 March 2008}}</ref> and was mentored by [[IIM Bangalore]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.mbauniverse.com/article/id/4101/IIM-Trichy |title=Foundation laid |access-date=6 January 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110907035159/http://www.mbauniverse.com/article/id/4101/IIM-Trichy |archive-date=7 September 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> It was the 11th IIM to be set up in India. Classes for the first batch began on 15 June 2011.<ref>{{cite news |url= http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/article2108504.ece |title=The Hindu : NATIONAL / TAMIL NADU : IIM-Tiruchi off to a bright start |work=thehindu.com |accessdate=9 October 2011 |location=Chennai, India |date=16 June 2011}}</ref>\n\n==Campus==\nThe institute temporarily operated at [[National Institute of Technology, Tiruchirappalli]] campus and the permanent campus was inaugurated on 3 April 2017 by [[Prakash Javadekar]].<ref name=\"Narasimhan\">{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/management/iim-trichy-to-become-global-institute-in-10-years-management-116100900130_1.html|title=IIM-Trichy to become global institute in 10 years: Management|last=Narasimhan|first=T. E.|date=2016-10-09|newspaper=Business Standard India|access-date=2016-11-17}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/academy/report-prakash-javadekar-to-inaugurate-new-campus-building-for-iim-tiruchirapalli-2379442|title=Prakash Javadekar to inaugurate new campus building for IIM Tiruchirapalli {{!}} Latest News & Updates at Daily News & Analysis|date=2017-04-03|work=dna|access-date=2017-04-03|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\nIndian Institute of Management Tiruchirappalli's permanent campus is located on a {{convert|172.27|acre}} land.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.thehindubusinessline.com/on-campus/iim-trichy-starts-work-on-new-172-acre-campus/article6152112.ece |title=IIM Trichy starts work on new 172 acre campus |location=[[Trichy]] |work=[[The Hindu]] |date=26 June 2014}}</ref> In its full shape, the {{INRConvert|584|c}} permanent campus will consist of student hostels, faculty residences, a library, recreational facilities and a Management Development Centre.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/education/news/IIM-Trichy-to-move-into-its-own-campus-in-2015/articleshow/24725883.cms |title=IIM-Trichy to move into its own campus in 2015 |location=[[Trichy]]|work=[[The Times of India]] |date=26 October 2013}}</ref><ref name=\"Narasimhan\"/>\n\nThe Indian Institute of Management Trichy has set up a satellite campus at Chennai. It offers a two-year postgraduate programme for working professionals from this campus.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://articles.timesofindia.indiatimes.com/2012-07-07/news/32576765_1_iim-trichy-iim-kozhikode-pgpbm |title=Chennai Campus |location=[[Trichy]]|work=[[The Times of India]]|date=7 January 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Academic programs==\nIIM Trichy offers a two-year full-time residential Post Graduate Programme in Management (PGP), a two-year Post Graduate Programme in Business Management (PGPBM) for working executives at Chennai campus,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.iimtrichy.ac.in/home/academics/programs/ |title=Programme Offered |access-date=1 July 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110620081836/http://www.iimtrichy.ac.in/home/academics/programs/ |archive-date=20 June 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> and a Fellow Programme in Management (FPM) for doctoral candidates.\n\n==Rankings==\n{{Infobox India university ranking\n|type=Institute\n|NIRF_B_2018= 15\n}}\nIIM Tiruchirappalli was ranked 15 in [[National Institutional Ranking Framework]] (NIRF) management school ranking of 2018.<ref name=Rankings_NIRF_B_2018/>\n\n== Events ==\nIIMT hosts several yearly events. Dhruva is a cultural and management [[Cultural Festival (India)|fest]] held in the second half of the month of October.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://dhruva.iimtrichy.ac.in/index.php|title=Dhruva 16|website=dhruva.iimtrichy.ac.in|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/iim-trichy-celebrates-its-management-and-cultural-fest-dhruva/article9261648.ece|title=IIM Trichy celebrates its management and cultural fest, Dhruva|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2016-10-24|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/dhruva16-a-business-and-cultural-extravaganza/article9132375.ece|title=Dhruva\u201916: A business and cultural extravaganza|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2016-09-21|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> E-Summit is an entrepreneurial summit held in the month of November.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://esummit.iimtrichy.ac.in/|title=E-Summit|website=esummit.iimtrichy.ac.in|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/iim-trichy-conducts-inaugural-edition-of-esummit-2016/article9344999.ece|title=IIM Trichy conducts inaugural edition of E-Summit 2016|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2016-11-14|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> HR Conclave is an industry-academia interaction event focused on [[Human Resources]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://hrconclave.iimtrichy.ac.in/|title=IIMT -  HR Conclave 2016|last=Trichy|first=IIM|website=hrconclave.iimtrichy.ac.in|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-features/tp-downtown/hr-conclave/article9301971.ece|title=HR conclave|date=2016-11-04|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/iim-trichys-hr-conclave-2015-on-oct-17/article7766335.ece|title=IIM Trichy\u2019s HR Conclave 2015 on Oct 17|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2015-10-15|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.bloncampus.com/b-school-corner/iim-trichy-conducts-its-fourth-hr-conclave/article9312116.ece|title=The role of data analytics in human resource management|last=BLoC|first=Team|date=2016-11-06|newspaper=BLoC|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> Other events include Sanskriti - an annual war of sections,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://insideiim.com/Sanskriti-4-0-at-iim-trichy-battle-of-the-sections/|title=Sanskriti 4.0 at IIM Trichy \u2013 Battle of The Sections {{!}} InsideIIM.com|website=insideiim.com|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> Sangram - an inter-IIM sports meet,<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportskeeda.com/general-sports/iim-kozhikode-stage-sangram-2015-second-week-november|title=IIM Kozhikode to stage Sangram 2015 in the second week of November|date=2015-11-12|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.sportskeeda.com/general-sports/inter-iim-sports-meet-sangram-concludes-iim-bangalore-take-victory|title=IIM-Bangalore take top prize at Sangram, the Inter-IIM sports meet|date=2015-11-19|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref> and Kurukshetra - an inter-section sports tournament.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://students.iimtrichy.ac.in/|title=IIMT Student Portal|website=students.iimtrichy.ac.in|access-date=2016-11-18}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://iimtrichy.ac.in/ Official website]\n\n{{Indian Institutes of Management}}\n{{Tiruchirappalli}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Indian Institute Of Management Tiruchirappalli}}\n[[Category:Indian Institutes of Management|TRICHY]]\n[[Category:Business schools in Tamil Nadu]]\n[[Category:Universities and colleges in Tiruchirappalli|IIM]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 2011]]\n[[Category:2011 establishments in India]]\n", "name_user": "Soundarya97", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added the Admission Process paragraph", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Indian_Institute_of_Management_Tiruchirappalli"}
